        <problem>
        <title>P12</title>
        <p>
            Recall that <m>I_{n,k}</m> is the number of permutations in <m>\ss_n</m> with <m>k</m> inversions, and <m>A_{n,k}</m> is the number of permutations in <m>\ss_n</m> with <m>k</m> descents. 
            Give a combinatorial proof that
            <me>
                I_{n,k}=I_{n,(n(n-1)/2)-k}
            </me>
            and 
            <me>
                A_{n,k}=A_{n,n-1-k} \, .
            </me>
        </p>
    </problem>
        <problem>
        <title>P13</title>
        <p>
            <ol>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        In the first part of this problem, you will prove by induction that <me>\sum_{j=1}^n j=\frac{n(n+1)}{2}\, .</me>
                        <ol>
                            <li>
                                <p>
                                    First, verify the <em>base case</em> for the induction argument, i.e., check that this is true for <m>n=1</m>.
                                </p>
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                <p>
                                    Second, assume that this is true for all values less than <m>n</m>.
                                    In particular, this means that we assume we have already verified that <me>\sum_{j=1}^{n-1}j=\frac{(n-1)n}{2}\, .</me>
                                    To prove that the <em>induction step</em> holds, use this to prove that the equation holds for <m>n</m> as follows: write <me>
                                        \sum_{j=1}^n j = \left(\sum_{j=1}^{n-1} j\right) + n 
                                    </me>
                                    and then substitute the formula for the <m>n-1</m> case and simplify with algebra.                             
                                </p>
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                <p>
                                    Explain in your own words why this shows that the formula is true for any positive integer <m>n</m>.
                                </p>
                            </li>
                        </ol>
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Prove by induction that <me>\sum_{j=1}^nj^2=\frac{n(n+1)(2n+1)}{6}\, .</me>
                    </p>
                </li>
            </ol>
            Comment for those who are interested: These two formulas are ones that students learn (and typically forget) in Calculus I. 
            However, these are special cases of a beautiful formula called Faulhaber's formula which is a formula for the sum of the <m>p</m>-th powers of the first <m>n</m> positive integers:
            <url href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Faulhaber%27s_formula" />.
        </p>
    </problem>

