    <problem>
        <title>P28</title>
        <p>
            Let <m>(\Omega, P)</m> be a finite probability space and let <m>X</m> be a random variable on <m>\Omega</m> such that <m>X(x)\geq 0</m> for every <m>x\in \Omega</m>.
            We define <m>P(X\geq a)</m> to be the probability that <m>X</m> takes on a value greater than or equal to <m>a</m>, i.e., 
            <me>
                P(X\geq a):= \sum_{x \in \Omega, X(x) \geq a} P(x) \, .
            </me>
            Prove that for any <m>a > 0</m>, the following inequality, which is known as <em>Markov's Inequality</em>, holds:
            <me>
                P(X\geq a)\leq \frac{E(X)}{a} \, .
            </me>
